introduction.p:
In this section we study logarithmic functions. For example,
	f(x)=\log_2 {x}
is a logarithmic function. In order to understand logarithmic functions better, we first investigate how they are related to more familiar functions, the exponential functions.

subsection.p:
A similar rule relates the operations of raising a base b to a power and taking a base b logarithm. y = \log_b {x}~~~~\text{if and only if}~~~~x=b^y So the function g(x)=\log_b {x} is the inverse function for f(x)=b^x. Each function undoes the effect of the other. For example, let f(x)=2^x and g(x)=\log_2 {x}. Start with x=3, apply f, and then apply g to the result.
x = \alert{3}~~~~~~\rightarrow~~~~~~f(3)=2^3=8~~~~~~\rightarrow~~~~~~g(8)=\log_2{8} = \alert{3}
We return to the original number, 3.

We can write these operations in one expression as
	\log_2(2^{\alert{3}}) = \alert{3}
(Remember the order of operations: do what's inside of parentheses first.) Because the log and the exponential are inverse functions, this identity holds for any value of x and any base b \gt 0.  That is
	\blert{\log_b(b^{x}) = x}
We can also apply the two functions in the opposite order, so that
	2^{\log_2{\alert{8}}} = \alert{8}
(This one is harder to see, but we compute the exponent, \log_2{8}, first.) And in general
	\blert{b^{\log_b{x}} = x}

solution.p:
Follow the order of operations and calculate
	T \amp =\dfrac{1}{0.028}{\log_{10}{\dfrac{1832}{15.3}+1}} = \dfrac{\log_{10}{120.739}}{0.028}
		 \amp \approx \dfrac{2.082}{0.028} \approx 74.35
A calculator keying sequence for the calculation is
	 \boxed{\text{LOG}}~~1832~~\boxed{\div}~~15.3~~\boxed{+}~~1~~\boxed{)}~~\boxed{\div}~~0.028~~\boxed{\text{ENTER}}

webwork.pg-code:
Context()->flags->set(useBaseTenLog=>1);
Context()->variables->add(t=>"Real", Df=>"Real", D0=>"Real");
$f = Formula("log(2)*t/(3log(Df/D0))");
$t = Compute("7");
$D0 = Compute("1");
$Df = Compute("1.05");
$answer = $f->eval(t=>$t, Df=>$Df, D0=>$D0)->with(
  tolType => 'absolute',
  tolerance => .51,
);

statement.p:
Which function grows more slowly for large values of x ?

f(x)=2x

f(x)=\log_2{x}

f(x)=\sqrt{x}

f(x)=\dfrac{x}{2}

solution.p:
We use the conversion formula to write the equation in exponential form.
	2x-8 \amp = 4^3 \amp \amp \glert{\text{Evaluate the power.}}
		2x-8 \amp = 64  \amp \amp \glert{\text{Solve for}~x.}
		 x \amp = 36
The solution is 36.

We use Property (1) of logarithms to rewrite the left-hand side as a single logarithm:
	\log_{10}{(x + 1)(x - 2)} = 1
Once the left-hand side is expressed as a single logarithm, we can rewrite the equation in exponential form as
	(x + 1)(x - 2) = 10^1
Simplifying the right side gives us a quadratic equation to solve.
	x^2 - x - 2 \amp = 10 \amp \amp \glert{\text{Subtract 10 from both sides.}}
		x^2 - x - 12 \amp = 0 \amp \amp \glert{\text{Factor the left side.}}
		(x - 4)(x + 3) \amp= 0 \amp \amp \glert{\text{Apply the zero-factor principle.}}
We find x = 4 or x = -3.  But we must check the original equation for extraneous solutions. The number -3 is not a solution of the original equation, because neither \log_{10}{(x + 1)} nor \log_{10}{(x - 2)} is defined for x = -3. The apparent solution x=-3 is extraneous, and the solution of the original equation is 4.

